Chapter 6 - Tokens
What is a Token?
Definition

A token is the smallest unit of text processed by a Large Language Model.

A token is not always a word.

Depending on the tokenizer, a token may represent:

A complete word
Part of a word
A punctuation mark
A number
A special symbol
Even a space in some tokenization schemes
Examples

Sentence:

Artificial Intelligence is amazing.

Possible tokenization:

Artificial
Intelligence
is
amazing
.

Five tokens.

Another example:

unbelievable

May become:

un
believ
able

Three tokens.

The exact tokenization depends on the tokenizer used by the model.

Why don't LLMs use words directly?

Computers cannot process natural language directly.

They only understand numbers.

Therefore:

Sentence

